# The enzarb operator must be able to create/update/delete Services for project pods.
# This permission is intentional and scoped to the operator's reconciliation needs.
KSV-0056

# The enzarb-deployer ClusterRole grants project service accounts the ability to manage
# Secrets in their own environment namespaces (e.g., image pull secrets, env secrets for CI/CD).
# This is intentional and scoped to deploy-<orgid>-<envslug> namespaces via RoleBindings.
KSV-0041

# The enzarb-deployer ClusterRole grants pods/exec (create) so tenants can shell into their own
# pods in their env namespace for debugging. Audited: the operator never creates
# Deployments/Jobs/Pods in deploy-<orgid>-<envslug> namespaces, and ACME HTTP-01 challenges are
# solved via a Gateway HTTPRoute rather than an ephemeral solver pod, so no foreign,
# more-privileged pod ever exists in-namespace to exec into — every pod there runs under the
# tenant's own ServiceAccount, which the anti-escalation RoleBinding-kind VAP already bounds.
KSV-0053

# The enzarb-operator ClusterRole grants "bind" on "roles" scoped to
# resourceNames: ["enzarb-deployer"] only, so the operator can bind the
# namespace-local Role it mirrors from the enzarb-deployer ClusterRole into
# each deploy namespace (see ensureDeployerRole/ensureDeployerRoleBinding).
# Kubernetes' native privilege-escalation check still applies on top of this —
# bind alone doesn't let the operator grant more than it already holds — and
# the enzarb-restrict-rolebinding-kind VAP prevents tenants from ever binding
# a ClusterRole directly.
KSV-0050
